               <msContents>
                  <summary>Four Gospels. Ministry of Tourism Number, T3-2-IV-1. Notes: <locus target="#11r">fols. 11r, </locus>: Record of Sale of house belonging to ደብተራ ቈጽሉ by his wife and son for 55 Ethiopian Birr to ሥላስ, in the time of Däjazmač ውቤ (1800-1867), with a long list of witnesses. <locus target="#12r">12r, </locus> (columns 1-2): Record of property of the church in 1890 EC. <locus target="#12r">12r, </locus>: List of the leaders of the church in their various assigned locations. <locus target="#12r">12r, </locus> (column 3): Record of Constitution (ንጽሕፍ ሥርዓተ ዚእሃ) of the church of Dabra Mahrat, also known as Dabra Birhan, with 77 priests፥ indicating that when a priest dies, they wait one year and then replace him. <locus target="#12v">12v, </locus>: various gult records of the church relating to various Dabtaras.  King Tewodros is mentioned. <locus target="#13r">13r, </locus>: land records are interspersed among the charts, including one dated to 1818 EC. <locus target="#17v">17v, </locus>: Many more records including one dates to 1787 EC and mentioning "our king Takla Giyorgis" (1779-1800). Another mentions "our king Egwala Tseyon" (1801-1818). <locus target="#20r">20r, </locus>: Record of reconciliation, which mentions the time of Ras Wolde Selassie ዎልደ ስላሴ 1745 - 28 May 1816. <locus target="#20v">20v</locus>: Record note of ownership of this book by Ras Wolde Selassie.</summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="ms_i1">
                     <textLang mainLang="gez">Gǝ‘ǝz</textLang>
                  </msItem>
